[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] AutoML potentially includes every stage from beginning with a raw dataset to building a machine learning model ready for deployment.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] AutoML was proposed as an artificial intelligence-based solution to the growing challenge of applying machine learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] The high degree of automation in AutoML aims to allow non-experts to make use of machine learning models and techniques without requiring them to become experts in machine learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] Automating the process of applying machine learning end-to-end additionally offers the advantages of producing simpler solutions, faster creation of those solutions, and models that often outperform hand-designed models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] Common techniques used in AutoML include hyperparameter optimization, meta-learning and neural architecture search.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] In a typical machine learning application, practitioners have a set of input data points to be used for training.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] The raw data may not be in a form that all algorithms can be applied to.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] To make the data amenable for machine learning, an expert may have to apply appropriate data pre-processing, feature engineering, feature extraction, and feature selection methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] After these steps, practitioners must then perform algorithm selection and hyperparameter optimization to maximize the predictive performance of their model.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] If deep learning is used, the architecture of the neural network must also be chosen manually by the machine learning expert.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] Each of these steps may be challenging, resulting in significant hurdles to using machine learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] AutoML aims to simplify these steps for non-experts, and to make it easier for them to use machine learning techniques correctly and effectively.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] AutoML plays an important role within the broader approach of automating data science, which also includes challenging tasks such as data engineering, data exploration and model interpretation and prediction.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] Automated machine learning can target various stages of the machine learning process.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] There are a number of key challenges being tackled around automated machine learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] A big issue surrounding the field is referred to as "development as a cottage industry".
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] This phrase refers to the issue in machine learning where development relies on manual decisions and biases of experts.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] This is contrasted to the goal of machine learning which is to create systems that can learn and improve from their own usage and analysis of the data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] Basically, it's the struggle between how much experts should get involved in the learning of the systems versus how much freedom they should be giving the machines.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] However, experts and developers must help create and guide these machines to prepare them for their own learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] To create this system, it requires labor intensive work with knowledge of machine learning algorithms and system design.
[src:neural-architecture-search/automated-machine-learning] Additionally, other challenges include meta-learning and computational resource allocation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The method constructs a probabilistic model of the unknown function, often a Gaussian process (GP), and uses the resulting predictive distribution to choose the next evaluation point.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] This choice is made by optimizing a sampling criterion, also called an acquisition function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Common applications include hyperparameter optimization in machine learning, where each trial may require training and validating a model, and engineering design problems driven by expensive numerical simulations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Early Bayesian approaches to global optimization include work by Harold J.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Kushner on locating extrema of noisy functions and work by Jonas Mockus on Bayesian methods for seeking extrema.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Expected improvement is a prominent sampling criterion in this line of work.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Jones, Matthias Schonlau, and William J.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Welch introduced the efficient global optimization (EGO) algorithm, which used a kriging or Gaussian-process model with expected improvement for expensive black-box functions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Later work extended Bayesian optimization to noisy observations, constraints, batch and parallel evaluations, multiple objectives, and mixed or high-dimensional search spaces.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] where ${\mathcal {X}}$ is a search space and f is an unknown objective function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] A maximization problem can be written in the same form by minimizing $-f$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Although the search space may in principle be continuous, discrete, categorical, or mixed, the standard formulation is most directly applicable to continuous, low- to moderate-dimensional domains.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Later methods attempt to relax these restrictions by addressing mixed variables, high-dimensional spaces, constraints, parallel evaluations, and multiple objectives.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] A useful distinction is between *noiseless* and *noisy* optimization.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Many real applications also involve constraints, parallel evaluations, or multiple objectives.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] These variants change how the probabilistic model, incumbent solution, and sampling criterion are defined.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] A typical Bayesian optimization procedure builds a sequence of evaluation points.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Starting from an initial design $X_{0}$ , the algorithm produces additional evaluation points $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] After n sequential evaluations, $X_{n}=X_{0}\cup \{x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}\}$ denotes the evaluated points and ${\mathcal {D}}_{n}$ denotes the corresponding observations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The next point $x_{n+1}$ , or a batch of points, is selected by optimizing a sampling criterion computed from the current probabilistic model.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Evaluate the objective function, and any constraints if present, at the initial design points.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Construct or update a probabilistic model using the observed data ${\mathcal {D}}_{n}$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Define a sampling criterion, also called an acquisition function or infill criterion, from the probabilistic model.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Optimize the sampling criterion to select $x_{n+1}$ , or a batch of points, for evaluation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Evaluate the selected point or points and update the data set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Repeat until an evaluation budget, convergence criterion, or stopping rule is reached.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The Bayesian strategy treats the unknown objective as a random function and places a prior over it.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The prior captures assumptions about the behavior of the function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] After observations are collected, the prior is updated to form a posterior distribution over the objective function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The posterior distribution is then used to construct the sampling criterion that determines the next query point.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization requires a probabilistic model of the unknown objective function and, when present, of unknown constraints.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Given the evaluations observed so far, the model gives a predictive distribution for unevaluated points in the search space.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Sampling criteria are defined from this predictive distribution, so the model provides both predicted objective values and uncertainty estimates.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Such probabilistic models are often called surrogate models or metamodels because they are used in place of direct evaluations of the expensive objective when choosing candidate points.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Gaussian process regression is the standard probabilistic model in classical presentations of Bayesian optimization and remains common in applications.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] A Gaussian process prior defines a distribution over functions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] After observations are collected, the posterior predictive mean and variance are used by sampling criteria such as expected improvement, probability of improvement, and upper confidence bound criteria.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Other probabilistic models can be used when the search space, dimensionality, or data size favors another representation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization is often described through a noiseless, single-objective problem, but the same model-based loop is adapted to several related settings.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] In noisy Bayesian optimization, evaluations return observations such as $y=f(x)+\varepsilon$ instead of exact values of the latent objective.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The probabilistic model can represent both uncertainty about f and observation noise.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Classical expected improvement over the best observed value is a noiseless criterion.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] In noisy settings, recommendation rules and sampling criteria may be defined for the latent objective, for future noisy observations, or for the value of information.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Examples include knowledge-gradient and information-theoretic criteria.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] In constrained Bayesian optimization, the objective is optimized subject to feasibility constraints.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] If the constraints are also unknown black-box functions, separate probabilistic models can be constructed for the objective and constraints, and the sampling criterion can combine predicted improvement with the probability of feasibility.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] In batch or parallel Bayesian optimization, the method proposes several candidate points before the corresponding observations are available.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Batch methods are useful when experiments, simulations, or machine-learning jobs can be executed concurrently.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] They may optimize a joint sampling criterion or choose points sequentially while accounting for pending evaluations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] In multi-objective Bayesian optimization, several objective functions are optimized at once and the result is typically an approximation to a Pareto front.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Methods include scalarization approaches such as ParEGO, which reduce the problem to a sequence of single-objective subproblems, and indicator-based approaches using criteria such as expected hypervolume improvement.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Constrained multi-objective Bayesian optimization combines these extensions by modeling objectives and constraints and using sampling criteria based on extended domination rules and expected hypervolume improvement.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] A sampling criterion, also called an acquisition function in the machine-learning literature or an infill criterion in surrogate-based optimization, scores candidate points using the current predictive distribution.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] It is usually inexpensive to evaluate and is optimized instead of the expensive objective function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Sampling criteria express the exploration-exploitation tradeoff by assigning high values to points with a low predicted objective value, high uncertainty, or both.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] A seminal example in the noiseless setting is expected improvement, which scores a candidate point by the posterior expected gain over the best value observed so far.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Expected improvement (EI) was used in the efficient global optimization (EGO) algorithm and remains a standard reference criterion for noiseless Bayesian optimization.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] In the noiseless minimization setting, let $f_{\min }$ be the best objective value observed so far and let ${\mathcal {D}}$ denote the data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] where $\Phi$ and $\phi$ are the cumulative distribution function and probability density function of the standard normal distribution.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] EI is therefore large when the model predicts a low objective value, when uncertainty is high, or both.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The sampling criterion is usually cheap to evaluate relative to the objective, but optimizing it can still be a nonconvex auxiliary problem.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Its optimum is often sought by discretization, multi-start local optimization, or deterministic numerical methods such as Newton's method and quasi-Newton methods like the Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Stochastic methods are also used for this auxiliary search, especially for multimodal or mixed-variable criteria.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Examples include genetic algorithms and other evolutionary algorithms, as well as sequential Monte Carlo methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Several derivative-free optimization methods use probability distributions without modeling the unknown objective function itself.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Estimation of distribution algorithms build and sample explicit probabilistic models of selected candidate solutions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] The cross-entropy method and CMA-ES also update parametric sampling distributions, with CMA-ES adapting the mean, step size, and covariance matrix of a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] These methods use objective values to update a distribution over candidate points.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] In Bayesian optimization, the probabilistic model instead represents the objective or constraints, and the next point is chosen by optimizing a criterion derived from that model.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Gaussian-process sequential design is also used in reliability analysis to estimate a probability of failure.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] For a limit-state function f , random input X , and threshold t , the target may be $\mathbb {P} (f(X)\leq t)$ , or more generally the measure of an excursion set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Stepwise uncertainty reduction strategies choose evaluations to reduce uncertainty about this probability, rather than to locate the minimizer or maximizer of f .
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization is also related to multi-armed bandit problems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Both study sequential decisions that trade off exploration and exploitation, and criteria such as upper confidence bounds and Thompson sampling appear in both settings.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] A common distinction is that bandit algorithms are often formulated to control cumulative regret over a sequence of actions, while Bayesian optimization often emphasizes finding a good optimizer of an expensive function after a small evaluation budget.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization is used in applications where objective evaluations are costly.
[src:neural-architecture-search/bayesian-optimization] Examples discussed in surveys and textbooks include hyperparameter optimization and algorithm configuration, engineering design and simulation-based optimization, robotics, sensor networks, and experimental design in the physical sciences.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:neural-architecture-search/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] In machine learning, **hyperparameter optimization** or tuning is the problem of choosing a set of optimal hyperparameters for a learning algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] A hyperparameter is a parameter whose value is used to control the learning process, which must be configured before the process starts.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperparameter optimization determines the set of hyperparameters that yields an optimal model which minimizes a predefined loss function on a given data set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] The objective function takes a set of hyperparameters and returns the associated loss.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Cross-validation is often used to estimate this generalization performance, and therefore choose the set of values for hyperparameters that maximize it.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] The traditional method for hyperparameter optimization has been *grid search*, or a *parameter sweep*, which is simply an exhaustive searching through a manually specified subset of the hyperparameter space of a learning algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] A grid search algorithm must be guided by some performance metric, typically measured by cross-validation on the training set or evaluation on a hold-out validation set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Since the parameter space of a machine learner may include real-valued or unbounded value spaces for certain parameters, manually set bounds and discretization may be necessary before applying grid search.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] For example, a typical soft-margin SVM classifier equipped with an RBF kernel has at least two hyperparameters that need to be tuned for good performance on unseen data: a regularization constant *C* and a kernel hyperparameter γ.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search then trains an SVM with each pair (*C*, γ) in the Cartesian product of these two sets and evaluates their performance on a held-out validation set (or by internal cross-validation on the training set, in which case multiple SVMs are trained per pair).
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Finally, the grid search algorithm outputs the settings that achieved the highest score in the validation procedure.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search suffers from the curse of dimensionality, but is often embarrassingly parallel because the hyperparameter settings it evaluates are typically independent of each other.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search replaces the exhaustive enumeration of all combinations by selecting them randomly.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be simply applied to the discrete setting described above, but also generalizes to continuous and mixed spaces.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] A benefit over grid search is that random search can explore many more values than grid search could for continuous hyperparameters.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] It can outperform Grid search, especially when only a small number of hyperparameters affects the final performance of the machine learning algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] In this case, the optimization problem is said to have a low intrinsic dimensionality.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search is also embarrassingly parallel, and additionally allows the inclusion of prior knowledge by specifying the distribution from which to sample.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Despite its simplicity, random search remains one of the important base-lines against which to compare the performance of new hyperparameter optimization methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Bayesian optimization is a global optimization method for noisy black-box functions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Applied to hyperparameter optimization, Bayesian optimization builds a probabilistic model of the function mapping from hyperparameter values to the objective evaluated on a validation set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] By iteratively evaluating a promising hyperparameter configuration based on the current model, and then updating it, Bayesian optimization aims to gather observations revealing as much information as possible about this function and, in particular, the location of the optimum.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] It tries to balance exploration (hyperparameters for which the outcome is most uncertain) and exploitation (hyperparameters expected close to the optimum).
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] In practice, Bayesian optimization has been shown to obtain better results in fewer evaluations compared to grid search and random search, due to the ability to reason about the quality of experiments before they are run.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] For specific learning algorithms, it is possible to compute the gradient with respect to hyperparameters and then optimize the hyperparameters using gradient descent.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] The first usage of these techniques was focused on neural networks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Since then, these methods have been extended to other models such as support vector machines or logistic regression.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] A different approach in order to obtain a gradient with respect to hyperparameters consists in differentiating the steps of an iterative optimization algorithm using automatic differentiation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] A more recent work along this direction uses the implicit function theorem to calculate hypergradients and proposes a stable approximation of the inverse Hessian.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] The method scales to millions of hyperparameters and requires constant memory.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] In a different approach, a hypernetwork is trained to approximate the best response function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] One of the advantages of this method is that it can handle discrete hyperparameters as well.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Self-tuning networks offer a memory efficient version of this approach by choosing a compact representation for the hypernetwork.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Apart from hypernetwork approaches, gradient-based methods can be used to optimize discrete hyperparameters also by adopting a continuous relaxation of the parameters.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Such methods have been extensively used for the optimization of architecture hyperparameters in neural architecture search.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization is a methodology for the global optimization of noisy black-box functions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] In hyperparameter optimization, evolutionary optimization uses evolutionary algorithms to search the space of hyperparameters for a given algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Repeat steps 2-4 until satisfactory algorithm performance is reached or is no longer improving.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization has been used in hyperparameter optimization for statistical machine learning algorithms, automated machine learning, typical neural network and deep neural network architecture search, as well as training of the weights in deep neural networks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Population Based Training (PBT) learns both hyperparameter values and network weights.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Multiple learning processes operate independently, using different hyperparameters.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] As with evolutionary methods, poorly performing models are iteratively replaced with models that adopt modified hyperparameter values and weights based on the better performers.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] This replacement model warm starting is the primary differentiator between PBT and other evolutionary methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT thus allows the hyperparameters to evolve and eliminates the need for manual hypertuning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] The process makes no assumptions regarding model architecture, loss functions or training procedures.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT and its variants are adaptive methods: they update hyperparameters during the training of the models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] On the contrary, non-adaptive methods have the sub-optimal strategy to assign a constant set of hyperparameters for the whole training.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] A class of early stopping-based hyperparameter optimization algorithms is purpose-built for large search spaces of continuous and discrete hyperparameters, particularly when the computational cost to evaluate the performance of a set of hyperparameters is high.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Irace implements the iterated racing algorithm, that focuses the search around the most promising configurations, using statistical tests to discard the ones that perform poorly.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Another early stopping hyperparameter optimization algorithm is successive halving (SHA), which begins as a random search but periodically prunes low-performing models, thereby focusing computational resources on more promising models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Asynchronous successive halving (ASHA) further improves upon SHA's resource utilization profile by removing the need to synchronously evaluate and prune low-performing models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperband is a higher level early stopping-based algorithm that invokes SHA or ASHA multiple times with varying levels of pruning aggressiveness, in order to be more widely applicable and with fewer required inputs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] RBF and spectral approaches have also been developed.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] When hyperparameter optimization is done, the set of hyperparameters are often fitted on a training set and selected based on the generalization performance, or score, of a validation set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] However, this procedure is at risk of overfitting the hyperparameters to the validation set.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] Therefore, the generalization performance score of the validation set (which can be several sets in the case of a cross-validation procedure) cannot be used to simultaneously estimate the generalization performance of the final model.
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] In order to do so, the generalization performance has to be evaluated on a set independent (which has no intersection) of the set (or sets) used for the optimization of the hyperparameters, otherwise the performance might give a value which is too optimistic (too large).
[src:neural-architecture-search/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be done on a second test set, or through an outer cross-validation procedure called nested cross-validation, which allows an unbiased estimation of the generalization performance of the model, taking into account the bias due to the hyperparameter optimization.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] NAS is closely related to hyperparameter optimization and meta-learning and is a subfield of automated machine learning (AutoML).
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Reinforcement learning (RL) can underpin a NAS search strategy.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Barret Zoph and Quoc Viet Le applied NAS with RL targeting the CIFAR-10 dataset and achieved a network architecture that rivals the best manually-designed architecture for accuracy, with an error rate of 3.65, 0.09 percent better and 1.05x faster than a related hand-designed model.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] On the Penn Treebank dataset, that model composed a recurrent cell that outperforms LSTM, reaching a test set perplexity of 62.4, or 3.6 perplexity better than the prior leading system.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] On the PTB character language modeling task it achieved bits per character of 1.214.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Learning a model architecture directly on a large dataset can be a lengthy process.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] NASNet addressed this issue by transferring a building block designed for a small dataset to a larger dataset.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] For the reduction cell, the initial operation applied to the cell's inputs uses a stride of two (to reduce the height and width).
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The learned aspect of the design included elements such as which lower layer(s) each higher layer took as input, the transformations applied at that layer and to merge multiple outputs at each layer.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] In the studied example, the best convolutional layer (or "cell") was designed for the CIFAR-10 dataset and then applied to the ImageNet dataset by stacking copies of this cell, each with its own parameters.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The approach yielded accuracy of 82.7% top-1 and 96.2% top-5.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] This exceeded the best human-invented architectures at a cost of 9 billion fewer FLOPS—a reduction of 28%.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The system continued to exceed the manually-designed alternative at varying computation levels.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The image features learned from image classification can be transferred to other computer vision problems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] E.g., for object detection, the learned cells integrated with the Faster-RCNN framework improved performance by 4.0% on the COCO dataset.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] In the so-called Efficient Neural Architecture Search (ENAS), a controller discovers architectures by learning to search for an optimal subgraph within a large graph.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The controller is trained with policy gradient to select a subgraph that maximizes the validation set's expected reward.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The model corresponding to the subgraph is trained to minimize a canonical cross entropy loss.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Multiple child models share parameters, ENAS requires fewer GPU-hours than other approaches and 1000-fold less than "standard" NAS.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] On CIFAR-10, the ENAS design achieved a test error of 2.89%, comparable to NASNet.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] On Penn Treebank, the ENAS design reached test perplexity of 55.8.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] An alternative approach to NAS is based on evolutionary algorithms, which has been employed by several groups.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] An Evolutionary Algorithm for Neural Architecture Search generally performs the following procedure.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] First a pool consisting of different candidate architectures along with their validation scores (fitness) is initialised.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] At each step the architectures in the candidate pool are mutated (e.g.: 3x3 convolution instead of a 5x5 convolution).
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Next the new architectures are trained from scratch for a few epochs and their validation scores are obtained.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] This is followed by replacing the lowest scoring architectures in the candidate pool with the better, newer architectures.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] This procedure is repeated multiple times and thus the candidate pool is refined over time.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Mutations in the context of evolving ANNs are operations such as adding or removing a layer, which include changing the type of a layer (e.g., from convolution to pooling), changing the hyperparameters of a layer, or changing the training hyperparameters.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] On CIFAR-10 and ImageNet, evolution and RL performed comparably, while both slightly outperformed random search.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Bayesian Optimization (BO), which has proven to be an efficient method for hyperparameter optimization, can also be applied to NAS.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] In this context, the objective function maps an architecture to its validation error after being trained for a number of epochs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] At each iteration, BO uses a surrogate to model this objective function based on previously obtained architectures and their validation errors.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] One then chooses the next architecture to evaluate by maximizing an acquisition function, such as expected improvement, which provides a balance between exploration and exploitation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Acquisition function maximization and objective function evaluation are often computationally expensive for NAS, and make the application of BO challenging in this context.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Recently, BANANAS has achieved promising results in this direction by introducing a high-performing instantiation of BO coupled to a neural predictor.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Another group used a hill climbing procedure that applies network morphisms, followed by short cosine-annealing optimization runs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The approach yielded competitive results, requiring resources on the same order of magnitude as training a single network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] E.g., on CIFAR-10, the method designed and trained a network with an error rate below 5% in 12 hours on a single GPU.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] While most approaches solely focus on finding architecture with maximal predictive performance, for most practical applications other objectives are relevant, such as memory consumption, model size or inference time (i.e., the time required to obtain a prediction).
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Because of that, researchers created a multi-objective search.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] LEMONADE is an evolutionary algorithm that adopted Lamarckism to efficiently optimize multiple objectives.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] In every generation, child networks are generated to improve the Pareto frontier with respect to the current population of ANNs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Neural Architect is claimed to be a resource-aware multi-objective RL-based NAS with network embedding and performance prediction.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Network embedding encodes an existing network to a trainable embedding vector.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Based on the embedding, a controller network generates transformations of the target network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] A multi-objective reward function considers network accuracy, computational resource and training time.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The reward is predicted by multiple performance simulation networks that are pre-trained or co-trained with the controller network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The controller network is trained via policy gradient.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Following a modification, the resulting candidate network is evaluated by both an accuracy network and a training time network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The results are combined by a reward engine that passes its output back to the controller network.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] RL or evolution-based NAS require thousands of GPU-days of searching/training to achieve state-of-the-art computer vision results as described in the NASNet, mNASNet and MobileNetV3 papers.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] To reduce computational cost, many recent NAS methods rely on the weight-sharing idea.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] In this approach, a single overparameterized supernetwork (also known as the one-shot model) is defined.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] A supernetwork is a very large Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) whose subgraphs are different candidate neural networks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Thus, in a supernetwork, the weights are shared among a large number of different sub-architectures that have edges in common, each of which is considered as a path within the supernet.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The essential idea is to train one supernetwork that spans many options for the final design rather than generating and training thousands of networks independently.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] In addition to the learned parameters, a set of architecture parameters are learnt to depict preference for one module over another.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Such methods reduce the required computational resources to only a few GPU days.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] More recent works further combine this weight-sharing paradigm, with a continuous relaxation of the search space, which enables the use of gradient-based optimization methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] These approaches are generally referred to as differentiable NAS and have proven very efficient in exploring the search space of neural architectures.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] One of the most popular algorithms amongst the gradient-based methods for NAS is DARTS.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] However, DARTS faces problems such as performance collapse due to an inevitable aggregation of skip connections and poor generalization which were tackled by many future algorithms.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Methods like aim at robustifying DARTS and making the validation accuracy landscape smoother by introducing a Hessian norm based regularisation and random smoothing/adversarial attack respectively.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] The cause of performance degradation is later analyzed from the architecture selection aspect.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Differentiable NAS has shown to produce competitive results using a fraction of the search-time required by RL-based search methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] For example, FBNet (which is short for Facebook Berkeley Network) demonstrated that supernetwork-based search produces networks that outperform the speed-accuracy tradeoff curve of mNASNet and MobileNetV2 on the ImageNet image-classification dataset.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] FBNet accomplishes this using over 400x *less* search time than was used for mNASNet.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Neural architecture search often requires large computational resources, due to its expensive training and evaluation phases.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] This further leads to a large carbon footprint required for the evaluation of these methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] To overcome this limitation, NAS benchmarks have been introduced, from which one can either query or predict the final performance of neural architectures in seconds.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] A NAS benchmark is defined as a dataset with a fixed train-test split, a search space, and a fixed training pipeline (hyperparameters).
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] There are primarily two types of NAS benchmarks: a surrogate NAS benchmark and a tabular NAS benchmark.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] A surrogate benchmark uses a surrogate model (e.g.: a neural network) to predict the performance of an architecture from the search space.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] On the other hand, a tabular benchmark queries the actual performance of an architecture trained up to convergence.
[src:neural-architecture-search/neural-architecture-search] Both of these benchmarks are queryable and can be used to efficiently simulate many NAS algorithms using only a CPU to query the benchmark instead of training an architecture from scratch.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In machine learning and optimal control, **reinforcement learning** (**RL**) is concerned with how an intelligent agent should take actions in a dynamic environment in order to maximize a reward signal.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is one of the three basic machine learning paradigms, alongside supervised learning and unsupervised learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] While supervised learning and unsupervised learning algorithms respectively attempt to discover patterns in labeled and unlabeled data, reinforcement learning involves training an agent through interactions with its environment.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] To learn to maximize rewards from these interactions, the agent makes decisions between trying new actions to learn more about the environment (exploration), or using current knowledge of the environment to take the best action (exploitation).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The search for the optimal balance between these two strategies is known as the exploration–exploitation dilemma.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The environment is typically stated in the form of a Markov decision process, as many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The main difference between classical dynamic programming methods and reinforcement learning algorithms is that the latter do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the Markov decision process, and they target large Markov decision processes where exact methods become infeasible.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Due to its generality, reinforcement learning is studied in many disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimization, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, and statistics.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The purpose of reinforcement learning is for the agent to learn an optimal (or near-optimal) policy that maximizes the reward function or other user-provided reinforcement signal that accumulates from immediate rewards.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This is similar to processes that appear to occur in animal psychology.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] For example, biological brains are hardwired to interpret signals such as pain and hunger as negative reinforcements, and interpret pleasure and food intake as positive reinforcements.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In some circumstances, animals learn to adopt behaviors that optimize these rewards.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This suggests that animals are capable of reinforcement learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] A basic reinforcement learning agent interacts with its environment in discrete time steps.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] At each time step t, the agent receives the current state $S_{t}$ and reward $R_{t}$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] It then chooses an action $A_{t}$ from the set of available actions, which is subsequently sent to the environment.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The environment moves to a new state $S_{t+1}$ and the reward $R_{t+1}$ associated with the *transition* $(S_{t},A_{t},S_{t+1})$ is determined.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] that maximizes the expected cumulative reward.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Formulating the problem as a Markov decision process assumes the agent directly observes the current environmental state; in this case, the problem is said to have *full observability*.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] If the agent only has access to a subset of states, or if the observed states are corrupted by noise, the agent is said to have *partial observability*, and formally the problem must be formulated as a partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In both cases, the set of actions available to the agent can be restricted.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] For example, the state of an account balance could be restricted to be positive; if the current value of the state is 3 and the state transition attempts to reduce the value by 4, the transition will not be allowed.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] When the agent's performance is compared to that of an agent that acts optimally, the difference in performance yields the notion of regret.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In order to act near optimally, the agent must reason about long-term consequences of its actions (i.e., maximize future rewards), although the immediate reward associated with this might be negative.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Thus, reinforcement learning is particularly well-suited to problems that include a long-term versus short-term reward trade-off.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] It has been applied successfully to various problems, including energy storage, robot control, photovoltaic generators, backgammon, checkers, Go (AlphaGo), and autonomous driving systems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Two elements make reinforcement learning powerful: the use of samples to optimize performance, and the use of function approximation to deal with large environments.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The first two of these problems could be considered planning problems (since some form of model is available), while the last one could be considered to be a genuine learning problem.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] However, reinforcement learning converts both planning problems to machine learning problems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The trade-off between exploration and exploitation has been most thoroughly studied through the multi-armed bandit problem and for finite state space Markov decision processes in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning requires clever exploration mechanisms; randomly selecting actions, without reference to an estimated probability distribution, shows poor performance.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The case of (small) finite Markov decision processes is relatively well understood.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] However, due to the lack of algorithms that scale well with the number of states (or scale to problems with infinite state spaces), simple exploration methods are the most practical.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] One such method is $\varepsilon$ -greedy, where $0<\varepsilon <1$ is a parameter controlling the amount of exploration vs. exploitation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] With probability $1-\varepsilon$ , exploitation is chosen, and the agent chooses the action that it believes has the best long-term effect (ties between actions are broken uniformly at random).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Alternatively, with probability $\varepsilon$ , exploration is chosen, and the action is chosen uniformly at random. $\varepsilon$ is usually a fixed parameter but can be adjusted either according to a schedule (making the agent explore progressively less), or adaptively based on heuristics.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Even if the issue of exploration is disregarded and even if the state was observable (assumed hereafter), the problem remains to use past experience to find out which actions lead to higher cumulative rewards.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The policy map gives the probability of taking action a when in state s .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] There are also deterministic policies $\pi$ for which $\pi (s)$ denotes the action that should be played at state s .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The state-value function $V_{\pi }(s)$ is defined as, *expected discounted return* starting with state s , i.e. $S_{0}=s$ , and successively following policy $\pi$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Hence, roughly speaking, the value function estimates "how good" it is to be in a given state.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] where $R_{t+1}$ is the reward for transitioning from state $S_{t}$ to $S_{t+1}$ , $0\leq \gamma <1$ is the discount rate. $\gamma$ is less than 1, so rewards in the distant future are weighted less than rewards in the immediate future.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The algorithm must find a policy with maximum expected discounted return.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] From the theory of Markov decision processes it is known that, without loss of generality, the search can be restricted to the set of so-called *stationary* policies.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] A policy is *stationary* if the action-distribution returned by it depends only on the last state visited (from the observation agent's history).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The search can be further restricted to *deterministic* stationary policies.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] A *deterministic stationary* policy deterministically selects actions based on the current state.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Since any such policy can be identified with a mapping from the set of states to the set of actions, these policies can be identified with such mappings with no loss of generality.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] One problem with this is that the number of policies can be large, or even infinite.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Another is that the variance of the returns may be large, which requires many samples to accurately estimate the discounted return of each policy.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] These problems can be ameliorated if we assume some structure and allow samples generated from one policy to influence the estimates made for others.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The two main approaches for achieving this are value function estimation and direct policy search.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Value function approaches attempt to find a policy that maximizes the discounted return by maintaining a set of estimates of expected discounted returns $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } [G]$ for some policy (usually either the "current" [on-policy] or the optimal [off-policy] one).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] These methods rely on the theory of Markov decision processes, where optimality is defined in a sense stronger than the one above: A policy is optimal if it achieves the best-expected discounted return from *any* initial state (i.e., initial distributions play no role in this definition).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Again, an optimal policy can always be found among stationary policies.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] where G stands for the discounted return associated with following $\pi$ from the initial state s .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] A policy that achieves these optimal state-values in each state is called *optimal*.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Clearly, a policy that is optimal in this sense is also optimal in the sense that it maximizes the expected discounted return, since $V^{*}(s)=\max _{\pi }\mathbb {E} [G\mid s,\pi ]$ , where s is a state randomly sampled from the distribution $\mu$ of initial states (so $\mu (s)=\Pr(S_{0}=s)$ ).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Although state-values suffice to define optimality, it is useful to define action-values.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] where G now stands for the random discounted return associated with first taking action a in state s and following $\pi$ , thereafter.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The theory of Markov decision processes states that if $\pi ^{*}$ is an optimal policy, we act optimally (take the optimal action) by choosing the action from $Q^{\pi ^{*}}(s,\cdot )$ with the highest action-value at each state, s .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The *action-value function* of such an optimal policy ( $Q^{\pi ^{*}}$ ) is called the *optimal action-value function* and is commonly denoted by $Q^{*}$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In summary, the knowledge of the optimal action-value function alone suffices to know how to act optimally.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Assuming full knowledge of the Markov decision process, the two basic approaches to compute the optimal action-value function are value iteration and policy iteration.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Both algorithms compute a sequence of functions $Q_{k}$ ( $k=0,1,2,\ldots$ ) that converge to $Q^{*}$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Computing these functions involves computing expectations over the whole state-space, which is impractical for all but the smallest (finite) Markov decision processes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In reinforcement learning methods, expectations are approximated by averaging over samples and using function approximation techniques to cope with the need to represent value functions over large state-action spaces.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods are used to solve reinforcement learning problems by averaging sample returns.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Unlike methods that require full knowledge of the environment's dynamics, Monte Carlo methods rely solely on actual or simulated experience—sequences of states, actions, and rewards obtained from interaction with an environment.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This makes them applicable in situations where the complete dynamics are unknown.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Learning from actual experience does not require prior knowledge of the environment and can still lead to optimal behavior.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] When using simulated experience, only a model capable of generating sample transitions is required, rather than a full specification of transition probabilities, which is necessary for dynamic programming methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods apply to episodic tasks, where experience is divided into episodes that eventually terminate.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Policy and value function updates occur only after the completion of an episode, making these methods incremental on an episode-by-episode basis, though not on a step-by-step (online) basis.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The term "Monte Carlo" generally refers to any method involving random sampling; however, in this context, it specifically refers to methods that compute averages from *complete* returns, rather than *partial* returns.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] These methods function similarly to the bandit algorithms, in which returns are averaged for each state-action pair.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The key difference is that actions taken in one state affect the returns of subsequent states within the same episode, making the problem non-stationary.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] To address this non-stationarity, Monte Carlo methods use the framework of general policy iteration (GPI).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] While dynamic programming computes value functions using full knowledge of the Markov decision process, Monte Carlo methods learn these functions through sample returns.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The value functions and policies interact similarly to dynamic programming to achieve optimality, first addressing the prediction problem and then extending to policy improvement and control, all based on sampled experience.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The first problem is corrected by allowing the procedure to change the policy (at some or all states) before the values settle.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This too may be problematic as it might prevent convergence.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Most current algorithms do this, giving rise to the class of *generalized policy iteration* algorithms.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Many *actor-critic* methods belong to this category.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The second issue can be corrected by allowing trajectories to contribute to any state-action pair in them.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This may also help to some extent with the third problem, although a better solution when returns have high variance is Sutton's temporal difference (TD) methods that are based on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The computation in TD methods can be incremental (when after each transition the memory is changed and the transition is thrown away), or batch (when the transitions are batched and the estimates are computed once based on the batch).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Batch methods, such as the least-squares temporal difference method, may use the information in the samples better, while incremental methods are the only choice when batch methods are infeasible due to their high computational or memory complexity.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Some methods try to combine the two approaches.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on temporal differences also overcome the fourth issue.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Another problem specific to TD comes from their reliance on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Most TD methods have a so-called $\lambda$ parameter $(0\leq \lambda \leq 1)$ that can continuously interpolate between Monte Carlo methods that do not rely on the Bellman equations and the basic TD methods that rely entirely on the Bellman equations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This can be effective in palliating this issue.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In order to address the fifth issue, *function approximation methods* are used.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] *Linear function approximation* starts with a mapping $\phi$ that assigns a finite-dimensional vector to each state-action pair.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The algorithms then adjust the weights, instead of adjusting the values associated with the individual state-action pairs.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on ideas from nonparametric statistics (which can be seen to construct their own features) have been explored.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Value iteration can also be used as a starting point, giving rise to the Q-learning algorithm and its many variants.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Including Deep Q-learning methods when a neural network is used to represent Q, with various applications in stochastic search problems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The problem with using action-values is that they may need highly precise estimates of the competing action values that can be hard to obtain when the returns are noisy, though this problem is mitigated to some extent by temporal difference methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Using the so-called compatible function approximation method compromises generality and efficiency.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] An alternative method is to search directly in (some subset of) the policy space, in which case the problem becomes a case of stochastic optimization.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The two approaches available are gradient-based and gradient-free methods.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Gradient-based methods (*policy gradient methods*) start with a mapping from a finite-dimensional (parameter) space to the space of policies: given the parameter vector $\theta$ , let $\pi _{\theta }$ denote the policy associated to $\theta$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Defining the performance function by $\rho (\theta )=\rho ^{\pi _{\theta }}$ under mild conditions this function will be differentiable as a function of the parameter vector $\theta$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] If the gradient of $\rho$ was known, one could use gradient ascent.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Since an analytic expression for the gradient is not available, only a noisy estimate is available.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Such an estimate can be constructed in many ways, giving rise to algorithms such as Williams's REINFORCE method (which is known as the likelihood ratio method in the simulation-based optimization literature).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] A large class of methods avoids relying on gradient information.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] These include simulated annealing, cross-entropy search or methods of evolutionary computation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Many gradient-free methods can achieve (in theory and in the limit) a global optimum.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods may converge slowly given noisy data.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] For example, this happens in episodic problems when the trajectories are long and the variance of the returns is large.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Value-function based methods that rely on temporal differences might help in this case.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In recent years, *actor–critic methods* have been proposed and performed well on various problems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods have been used in the robotics context.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Many policy search methods may get stuck in local optima (as they are based on local search).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Finally, all of the above methods can be combined with algorithms that first learn a model of the Markov decision process, the probability of each next state given an action taken from an existing state.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] For instance, the Dyna algorithm learns a model from experience, and uses that to provide more modelled transitions for a value function, in addition to the real transitions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Such methods can sometimes be extended to use of non-parametric models, such as when the transitions are simply stored and "replayed" to the learning algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Model-based methods can be more computationally intensive than model-free approaches, and their utility can be limited by the extent to which the Markov decision process can be learnt.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] There are other ways to use models than to update a value function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] For instance, in model predictive control the model is used to update the behavior directly.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The costly exploration needed to learn an optimal policy can be reduced if some supervised data is available.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This can be achieved for instance by learning a crude control policy and using this to initialize the Q table intelligently instead of with zeros.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Both the asymptotic and finite-sample behaviors of most algorithms are well understood.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Algorithms with provably (i.e. in a way that can be proved) good online performance (addressing the exploration issue) are known.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Efficient exploration of Markov decision processes is given in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Finite-time performance bounds have also appeared for many algorithms, but these bounds are expected to be rather loose and thus more work is needed to better understand the relative advantages and limitations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] For incremental algorithms, asymptotic convergence issues have been settled.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Temporal-difference-based algorithms converge under a wider set of conditions than was previously possible (for example, when used with arbitrary, smooth function approximation).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Associative reinforcement learning tasks combine facets of stochastic learning automata tasks and supervised learning pattern classification tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In associative reinforcement learning tasks, the learning system interacts in a closed loop with its environment.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This approach extends reinforcement learning by using a deep neural network and without explicitly designing the state space.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The work on learning ATARI games by Google DeepMind increased attention to deep reinforcement learning or end-to-end reinforcement learning.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Adversarial deep reinforcement learning is an active area of research in reinforcement learning focusing on vulnerabilities of learned policies.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In this research area some studies initially showed that reinforcement learning policies are susceptible to imperceptible adversarial manipulations.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] While some methods have been proposed to overcome these susceptibilities, in the most recent studies it has been shown that these proposed solutions are far from providing an accurate representation of current vulnerabilities of deep reinforcement learning policies.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] By introducing fuzzy inference in reinforcement learning, approximating the state-action value function with fuzzy rules in continuous space becomes possible.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The IF - THEN form of fuzzy rules make this approach suitable for expressing the results in a form close to natural language.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Extending FRL with Fuzzy Rule Interpolation allows the use of reduced size sparse fuzzy rule-bases to emphasize cardinal rules (most important state-action values).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In inverse reinforcement learning (IRL), no reward function is given.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Instead, the reward function is inferred given an observed behavior from an expert.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The idea is to mimic observed behavior, which is often optimal or close to optimal.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] One popular IRL paradigm is named maximum entropy inverse reinforcement learning (MaxEnt IRL).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] MaxEnt IRL estimates the parameters of a linear model of the reward function by maximizing the entropy of the probability distribution of observed trajectories subject to constraints related to matching expected feature counts.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Recently it has been shown that MaxEnt IRL is a particular case of a more general framework named random utility inverse reinforcement learning (RU-IRL).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] RU-IRL is based on random utility theory and Markov decision processes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The utility function is modeled as a random variable to account for the ignorance of the observer regarding the features the observed agent actually considers in its utility function.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Multi-objective reinforcement learning (MORL) is a form of reinforcement learning concerned with conflicting alternatives.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] It is distinct from multi-objective optimization in that it is concerned with agents acting in environments.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Safe reinforcement learning (SRL) can be defined as the process of learning policies that maximize the expectation of the return in problems in which it is important to ensure reasonable system performance and/or respect safety constraints during the learning and/or deployment processes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] An alternative approach is risk-averse reinforcement learning, where instead of the *expected* return, a *risk-measure* of the return is optimized, such as the conditional value at risk (CVaR).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In addition to mitigating risk, the CVaR objective increases robustness to model uncertainties.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] However, CVaR optimization in risk-averse RL requires special care, to prevent gradient bias and blindness to success.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement learning (or self-learning), is a learning paradigm which does not use the concept of immediate reward $R_{a}(s,s')$ after transition from s to $s'$ with action a .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] It does not use an external reinforcement, it only uses the agent internal self-reinforcement.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The internal self-reinforcement is provided by mechanism of feelings and emotions.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In the learning process emotions are backpropagated by a mechanism of secondary reinforcement.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The learning equation does not include the immediate reward, it only includes the state evaluation.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Compute state evaluation $v(s')$ of how good it is to be in the consequence situation $s'$ .
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Initial conditions of the memory are received as input from the genetic environment.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] It is a system with only one input (situation), and only one output (action, or behavior).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement (self-learning) was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-reinforcement learning, named Crossbar Adaptive Array (CAA).
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence states.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Efficient comparison of RL algorithms is essential for research, deployment and monitoring of RL systems.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] To compare different algorithms on a given environment, an agent can be trained for each algorithm.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Since the performance is sensitive to implementation details, all algorithms should be implemented as closely as possible to each other.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] After the training is finished, the agents can be run on a sample of test episodes, and their scores (returns) can be compared.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Since episodes are typically assumed to be i.i.d, standard statistical tools can be used for hypothesis testing, such as T-test and permutation test.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This requires to accumulate all the rewards within an episode into a single number—the episodic return.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] However, this causes a loss of information, as different time-steps are averaged together, possibly with different levels of noise.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Whenever the noise level varies across the episode, the statistical power can be improved significantly, by weighting the rewards according to their estimated noise.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Despite significant advancements, reinforcement learning (RL) continues to face several challenges and limitations that hinder its widespread application in real-world scenarios.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] RL algorithms often require a large number of interactions with the environment to learn effective policies, leading to high computational costs and time-intensive to train the agent.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] For instance, OpenAI's Dota-playing bot utilized thousands of years of simulated gameplay to achieve human-level performance.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Techniques like experience replay and curriculum learning have been proposed to reduce sample inefficiency, but these techniques add more complexity and are not always sufficient for real-world applications.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Training RL models, particularly for deep neural network-based models, can be unstable and prone to divergence.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] A small change in the policy or environment can lead to extreme fluctuations in performance, making it difficult to achieve consistent results.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This instability is further enhanced in the case of the continuous or high-dimensional action space, where the learning step becomes more complex and less predictable.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The RL agents trained in specific environments often struggle to generalize their learned policies to new, unseen scenarios.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This is the major setback preventing the application of RL to dynamic real-world environments where adaptability is crucial.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] The challenge is to develop such algorithms that can transfer knowledge across tasks and environments without extensive retraining.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Designing appropriate reward functions is critical in RL because poorly designed reward functions can lead to unintended behaviors.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In addition, RL systems trained on biased data may perpetuate existing biases and lead to discriminatory or unfair outcomes.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Both of these issues requires careful consideration of reward structures and data sources to ensure fairness and desired behaviors.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] In recent years Since the early 2020s, reinforcement learning has become a significant concept in natural language processing (NLP), where tasks are often sequential decision-making rather than static classification.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is where an agent take actions in an environment to maximize the accumulation of rewards.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This framework is best fit for many NLP tasks, including dialogue generation, text summarization, and machine translation, where the quality of the output depends on optimizing long-term or human-centered goals rather than the prediction of single correct label.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Early application of RL in NLP emerged in dialogue systems, where conversation was determined as a series of actions optimized for fluency and coherence.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] These early attempts, including policy gradient and sequence-level training techniques, laid a foundation for the broader application of reinforcement learning to other areas of NLP.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] A major breakthrough happened with the introduction of reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), a method in which human feedback ratings are used to train a reward model that guides the RL agent.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] Unlike traditional rule-based or supervised systems, RLHF allows models to align their behavior with human judgments on complex and subjective tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This technique was initially used in the development of InstructGPT, an effective language model trained to follow human instructions and later in ChatGPT which incorporates RLHF for improving output responses and ensuring safety.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] More recently, researchers have explored the use of offline RL in NLP to improve dialogue systems without the need of live human interaction.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] These methods optimize for user engagement, coherence, and diversity based on past conversation logs and pre-trained reward models.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] One example is DeepSeek-R1, which incorporates multi-stage training and cold-start data before RL.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] DeepSeek-R1 achieves performance comparable to OpenAI-o1-1217 on reasoning tasks.
[src:neural-architecture-search/reinforcement-learning] This model was trained via large-scale RL without supervised fine-tuning (SFT) as a preliminary step.
